Alias can be created with `Users.settings.sendAs: create` only by a service account with  domain-wide authority, as can be withdrawn from the [documentation][1].

See [here][2] how to create a service account. You would need to create creadentials and store them on your drive e.g. as a `.p12` file.

Here is a sample how to set up a service account in Java:

``` lang:java
public class ServiceAccountJava

 {
    private static final String APPLICATION_NAME = &quot;XXX&quot;;
    private static final JsonFactory JSON_FACTORY = JacksonFactory.getDefaultInstance();
    private static final List&lt;String&gt; SCOPES = Collections.singletonList(XXX);
    public static void main(String... args)   throws IOException, GeneralSecurityException
{
    final NetHttpTransport HTTP_TRANSPORT = GoogleNetHttpTransport.newTrustedTransport();							
	 File pk12=new File(&quot;XXX.p12&quot;);		
	 String serviceAccount=&quot;XXX@XXX-XXX.iam.gserviceaccount.com&quot;;   
// 	Builder necessary for the ability to refresh tokens
     GoogleCredential getCredentials = new GoogleCredential.Builder()
      .setTransport(HTTP_TRANSPORT)
      .setJsonFactory(JSON_FACTORY)
      .setServiceAccountId(serviceAccount)
	  .setServiceAccountPrivateKeyFromP12File(pk12)	//RESOURCES_CLIENT_SECRETS_JSON, SRC_RESOURCES_KEY_P12
      .setServiceAccountScopes(SCOPES)
      .setServiceAccountUser(&quot;XXX&quot;)	//the user whom you want to impersonate
      .build();
       ...
    }
}

```


[1]:https://developers.google.com/gmail/api/v1/reference/users/settings/sendAs/create
[2]:https://developers.google.com/android/management/service-account

